Preheat the #oven{} to 220°C, bring a #large saucepan{} of water to the boil and boil
your kettle. Heat a drizzle of @oil{a drizzle} in a #frying pan{} on medium high heat
and add the @pancetta lardons{60%g}. Stir-fry until golden, ~{4-5%mins}, reducing
the heat slightly if needed. Meanwhile, halve, peel and thinly slice the
@echalion shallot{1}. Quarter the @chestnut mushrooms{150%g}. Pick the @thyme{4} leaves
from their stalks (discard the stalks).

When the pancetta is browned, add the @diced chicken thigh{260%g} with a grind of
@pepper{} and stir together. Stir fry with the pancetta until browned on the outside,
~{4-5%mins}. Next, add the shallots, mushrooms and thyme to the pan with a pinch
of @salt{pinch} and @pepper{}, stir together and cook until the veggies have softened,
another ~{4-5%mins}.

While the veggies cook, chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel)
and add to the pan of boiling water to cook for ~{15-20%mins}.
> TIP: The potato is cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Mix the @water{200%ml} from your kettle with the @red wine stock paste{28%g} in a
#jug{} and stir to dissolve.

When the veggies are soft, add the @tomato puree{30%g} to the pan, stir together and
cook for ~{1%minute}, then add the @plain flour{16%g}, stir again and cook for
~{2%mins} more. Pour in the red wine stock and add the @bay leaf{1}. Mix and bring
to a simmer. Add a pinch of salt and pepper and simmer until the mixture has thickened
and the chicken is cooked, ~{4-5%mins}.
> TIP: The chicken is cooked when it is no longer pink in the middle.

Pour the mixture into an #ovenproof dish{}. Trim the @puff pastry sheet{1} to the
size of the dish and lay the pastry on top of the filling.
> TIP: It doesn't matter if the pastry goes over the edge of the dish or just sits
on top inside the dish, it will depend on the size of your dish!

Prick a small hole through the top of the pastry (to allow the steam to escape!). Bake
your pie on the top shelf until golden brown, ~{15-20%mins}.

Whilst the pie cooks, roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{10%g}. When the potatoes
are done, drain them in a #colander{}, return to the pan (off the heat) and mash
with a #potato masher{} until smooth. Add the parsley, a knob of @butter{knob} and
a splash of @milk{a splash}(if you have some). Stir together until well combined.
Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if it needs it. Cover with a #lid{} to keep warm.
Serve the pie with the mash on the side and enjoy! Remember not to eat the bay leaf!